The ASEA Anchorage Next Wave Committee took a break from a beautiful Saturday to raise money for Rotary Cares for Kids. Foster Children all across Alaska tend to change homes with all their personal belongings in trash bags. This effort gives each kid a backpack or duffle with all the essentials they need in life (plus a stuffed animal for the youngest lil' Alaskans). Thank you Rotary of Alaska for all you do for our kids. We are proud to partner in this effort. After all - It takes a village to raise a child.

Contract Summary Term – 3 years to September 30, 2021. 6 – Salaries 2% effective/retroactive to October 1, 2018 2.5 % effective October 1, 2019 2.5% effective October 1, 2020. 9 – Special Pay Practices Weekend shift differential of $1.00 or 2.25?/hour for every weekend hour worked extended beyond those who work in Sheriff facilities to all members of the bargaining unit or DMH only? effective/retroactive October 1, 2018. Standby Pay increased from $1.50/hour bonus to $2.50 hour bonus up to a new maximum of $500.00/month, for those whose regular assignment is within FSP or EODT, including: LET, PMRT, AOT, School Threat Assessment Response Team. Sheriff and Probation Facility bonus increased from $50.00/pay period to $75.00/pay period effective October 1, 2019, and to $90.00/pay period effective October 1, 2020. Bonus pay for those assigned to/paired with law enforcement as follows: $150/month effective October 1, 2019, then increased to $180/month effective October 1, 2020.
Also in this section there is a commitment to creating work group to create a two-tiered “medically” qualified bilingual bonus for DHS employees. The County also agreed to consult with AFSCME 2712 to determine the feasibility of creating PSW III and MHC III items. 19 – Prof Dev & Training “Training requests shall not be denied on the basis of performance issues.” 10 – Paycheck Errors Added timeframes to the steps needed to correct said errors. 11 – Bulletin Boards “Management shall provide keys to any locked access bulletin board to one AFSCME designee.” 12 – Safety and Health Added language for ad hoc labor-management meetings to consult on Health and Safety issues. Also added language to increase the focus field-based safety quarterly during clinic/program-based Health and Safety Committee meetings. Lastly, added AFSCME Local 2712 participation in DMH Countywide Health and Safety Committee meetings. 20 – Mand Cont Ed Added language that: “Training requests shall not be denied on the basis of performance issues” and increased the number of hours granted for pre-approved home study courses to fulfill mandatory continuing education requirements for licensure from 12 of the 24 per year to 16 of the 24 per year, and expanded the language to include all Departments in which Local 2712 has members, including DPH and Public Defenders. 33 – Grievance Procedure Clean-up/clarifying language with respect to requesting mediation. 24 – Grievances General-In-Character – Clean up language with respect to timelines.

Register For Our Opioid Training Now!

The objective of the training is for workers to recognize the dangers of opioid related substances. The training will include best practices to avoid exposure and the employers’ responsibility under the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) Personal Protective Equipment Standard (29 CFR 1910.132) to issue gloves, safety glasses and masks to workers who may be involved in securing, handling or cleaning up illicit drugs. Workers will also be taught best practices for handling and disposing of used hypodermic needles and the employers’ responsibilities under OSHA’s Bloodborne Pathogen Standard (29 CFR 1910.1030). Workers will also be informed of the signs and symptoms of a drug overdose and the emergency steps that should be considered in responding to the situation.
Workers will learn about the life saving drug Naloxone (Narcan) and will be trained in how to administer the auto-injection and nasal forms of the medication. Students who successfully complete this course will receive a certificate for Adult First Aid/CPR & AED and an additional certificate in Opioid Rescue Techniques from AFSCME which is valid for two years.

Raises! Rights! Respect!
•Have you submitted your open window yet? Better get it in soon before it disappears. The County is proposing complete elimination and eradication of open window process.
•Bereavement time should be respected! No cuts to bereavement time!
•Does your wrist hurt? Does your neck ache? Have you lost your 20/20 vision? Stop stalling, stop putting it off because this time next year your worker’s comp benefits may not exist.
WILL YOU ALLOW THIS HAPPEN?
These are just some of the county's proposals and we still haven't heard them all
These are some of the issues we’re fighting for:
•We want the same rights that are part of the “SSA Cares” campaign to apply to workers. Integrity, Fairness, Compassion, Dignity, Respect, Courtesy….etc
•We want rational, measurable, achievable criteria for workers during performance evaluations
•Give probationary employees criteria they must meet to pass probation
•Give workers paid time off to seek treatment for workers comp. injuries

There is no workforce in the state of Washington that has more at stake in decisions made by the Legislature. The Legislature has control over our wages, benefits, and pensions. They adopt a state budget that determines the funding level for the services we provide. Every year they consider countless bills that can have an impact on everything from our working conditions to our job security.
We are the experts. We can tell the story about how we serve the public everyday, about the resources we need to be able to provide these critical services, and about the importance of being able to recruit and retain high-quality workforce. Lobby training is a fun way to learn how to get engaged and be an effective advocate for the public, our families and for ourselves.
